For each top CpG site, a cis SNP (1Mb distance) was identified influencing DNA methylation levels (1). We used the strength of association between the SNP and CpG together with the strength of association between CpG and liver enzyme to estimate the strength of association between SNP and liver enzyme (Supplementary Figure 2A). The predicted effect sizes and standard errors (Betapredicted and SEpredicted, respectively) were calculated as follows: Betapredicted= BetaCpG~SNP × BetaLiverEnzyme~CpG;
SEpredicted =√ SE 2 CpG~SNP × SE 2 LiverEnzyme~CpG + SE 2 CpG~SNP × Beta 2 LiverEnzyme~CpG + SE 2 LiverEnzyme~CpG × Beta2CpG~SNP
The expected strength of associations were compared to the observed associations using a test of interaction (2). Consistency between the expected and observed estimates from these analyses supports a causal relation and refutes residual confounding or reverse causation. To explore whether liver enzymes have a causal effect on CpGs, we applied the same principles to conduct a Mendelian Randomization study (Supplementary Figure 2B) using a genetic risk score composed of top SNPs previously reported in the largest genome wide association study on liver enzymes (3).
